Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Austerity Revolt Shakes Up Europe
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Austerity Revolt Shakes Up Europe

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Anti-austerity push rattles Europe. Overseas markets are tanking. Tokyo fell 2.8% while the FTSE is down 2%, Greece fell 6% and the euro briefly slid to its lowest level since January, as France and Greece put a big question mark over Europe's economic future. France's new president promises to soften austerity measures, but the NYT says, "at the end of the day, he is not repudiating a fiscal contract, and is unlikely to push outsize spending increases that would invite financial markets to attack France the way they have recently in Spain." And Germany isn't going to back down on austerity as long as Angela Merkel is in charge.
Greece is another story. The election there was basically a rebuke of the two main parties. And their struggle to win a parliamentary majority "raises questions about whether Athens can stay in the euro zone in the long run, and may spark a new wave of contagion to other member states," Reuters says.
The Washington Post says the pushback in Europe could hold tough lessons for the U.S. "Mitt Romney has vowed to cut the deficit at a faster pace than President Obama. But the mixed results of such policies in Europe … could make the argument for speedy deficit reduction increasingly difficult."
Meanwhile, there are new signs that all this uncertainty is causing European bank-funding markets to freeze up. At the end of March, 10 of Europe's biggest banks had parked a total of nearly $1.2 trillion of cash at central banks around the world a 12% jump since December and up 66% from the end of 2010, the WSJ reports.
THE WEEK AHEAD:
Weekly jobless claims are expected to increase slightly to 366,000 – adding to worries about the jobs slowdown. A couple of other reports should show that inflation is still subdued. On Thursday, April import prices are likely to come in 0.3% lower. And Friday the core producer-price index for April, which strips out food and energy costs, is expected to have increased 0.2% – a little less than the previous month. Lower energy are expected to lower the headline reading 0.1%, MarketBeat notes. And the Thomson-Reuters/University of Michigan preliminary May consumer-sentiment survey is expected to tick down to 76.3 from 76.4 at the end of April.
Earnings season is winding down, but there are a few big names reporting this week: Disney, Cisco, Priceline, and Macy's.
And Congress reconvenes after a week long break – the agenda includes Ron Paul-led hearings bashing the Federal Reserve and some partisan bickering over the deficit.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Austerity Revolt Shakes Up Europe

Headlines.Headline: Dealpolitik: Will Marietta's Bid for Vulcan Be the 2012 Hostile Deal of the Year?

PARAGRAPH.#text: Martin Marietta Material's $4.7 billion hostile bid for Vulcan Materials boils down an argument that Martin Marietta can do a better job running Vulcan.  And it is not just about the synergies from combining the two similar businesses, which produce similar products for the construction industry (synergies Vulcan apparently is more than a bit skeptical about). In Martin Marietta's words: "Vulcan shareholders have experienced several years of disappointing Vulcan performance, as Vulcan management has not taken the difficult actions required in an economic downturn." Martin Marietta proposes to make its CEO the CEO of the combined company to solve that problem. According to Martin Marietta, the two companies have been discussing a possible merger for over nine years, largely at the instigation of Vulcan.   But things fell apart for the final time in May of this year over a dispute between the CEOs about who would be top dog and the level of synergies they believe are available from the merger.

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Vulcan Materials Co. VMC third-quarter earnings plummeted 76% on weakened sales and margins, as the construction aggregates company's results fell short of analysts' views. Shares were down 6.1%, at $34.01 after hours. Through the close, the stock has fallen 31% so far this year. The company--a supplier of asphalt, cement and other mainstays of heavy construction--reported aggregates shipments fell 2.6%, as the average price for aggregates was flat. Despite the lower volume, Chairman and Chief Executive Don James said the company is "encouraged by underlying shipping trends." He said trailing 12-month shipments of aggregates have been increasing since February in spite of a labor strike affecting its customers in Illinois in the most recent period.
